    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-07-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-07-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="98"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d98">
                <head>No. 98.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hall</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Bayard</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States in Central
                                America</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Guatemala</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-07-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 20, 1887</date>. (Received August
                        9.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 690.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: On the 14th instant the Guatemalan Government
                    received from its minister in Mexico the telegram referred to in my dispatch No.
                    685 of the same date. In addition to the announcement that troops were in march
                    to the frontier, it contains a charge against the Guatemalan Government that its
                    agents had assaulted the Mexican secretary of legation.</p>
                <p>On a previous occasion Mr. Hosmer had called on Señor Garay to ascertain what
                    foundation there might be for the report from Mexico, that troops were marching
                    to the Guatemalan frontier. Señor Garay assured Mr. Hosmer that the report was
                    untrue, or rather that it was impossible. At the second interview, however,
                    Señor Garay confirmed the report.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry C. Hall.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
